## Engineering Philosophy

These principles guide how code is written in this project. They're not aspirational — they're operational.

### Simplicity First
Solve the problem with the minimum viable approach. Three similar lines of code beat a premature abstraction. Don't build for hypothetical futures — build for the requirement that exists today and refactor when the pattern actually emerges.

### Make It Work, Make It Right, Make It Fast — In That Order
Get something working first. Then clean it up. Then optimize if there's a measured need. Don't gold-plate on the first pass. Don't optimize without profiling.

### Tests Prove Behavior, Not Coverage
Write tests that verify the system does what users need. Test behavior at boundaries — inputs, outputs, edge cases, failure modes. Don't chase coverage percentages.

### Explicit Over Implicit
Name things clearly. Make data flow visible. Avoid magic. Comments explain *why*, not *what*.

### Own Your Failures Loudly
Fail fast, fail visibly. No silent swallowing of errors. No empty catch blocks. Validate at system boundaries; trust internal code.

### Small, Reversible Steps
Prefer small commits. Prefer incremental changes. Prefer approaches that are easy to back out of. The cost of a wrong decision is proportional to how hard it is to undo.

### Design Before You Build (When It Matters)
Not everything needs a design phase. But when there are multiple viable approaches, meaningful reversal costs, or cross-cutting concerns — slow down and think first.

